<p class="posted"><strong>Posted by Vamirez at August 31, 2004 04:00 AM</strong></p>
<p>I'm always happy to get information about the game that is not polluted by the sadly usual whining and complaining. I think the articles here are actually more objective than many. Loral talks about things which he thinks are positive, as well as about things he is concerned about. Its perfectly okay to say that something is good, by the way. Objectivity goes both ways - its not the act of finding all attributes of a subject one could possibly disagree to.</p>

<p>Now lets not get entangled in an objectivity discourse - of course, anything one says or writes is colored by one's own views and opinions. But I dare say trying to see the good and the bad is a lot more objective than just looking for things to complain about.</p>

<p>That said I think that if not every character got all spells and foci then that is not a design flaw. If there are more foci than can be equipped at one time, the result will be that different people will have different foci, giving them bonuses on different kinds of spells. Of course, some foci will be mainstream and some not, but essentially there will be more diversity among foci-using characters, which is, in my opinion, a good thing. The same applies to spells (and items). Its cool if one or two chars in your guild can cast a rare AE spell, while another has that special over-time heal, for example. If you want to farm rare drops, you know what to expect and shouldn't whine because its your own decision to do it. And no, its not SOE's obligation to make sure everyone gets all spells (or armor pieces, or mobs, or whatever).</p>

<p>Flame away ;-)</p>
